               <head>Petition</head>
               <msContents>
                  <summary>1 copy of ʿArz̤ah dāsht</summary>
                  <msItem class="http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85064905 http://lccn.loc.gov/n50002518 http://lccn.loc.gov/sh85064915" n="1" xml:id="Uk_Or_16933_17-item1">
                     <title xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="work_21853">ʿArz̤ah dāsht</title>
                     <title xml:lang="per" key="work_21853">عرضه داشت</title>
                     <note>
                        <p>Petition to unnamed royal addressee (with chatr) stating the receipt of reports on the disorder of palace arrangements and the addressee's distrust of attendants. Further, that the addressee (i.e. Emperor Shāh ʿĀlam) is being struck by hand and foot solely to extract objects (chīzī badast ārand). Reports the arrival of a person named Faz̤l ʿAlī Khān with several khilʿat from His Majesty. Although mentioned in an earlier shuqqah, it was thought prudent to remain cautious of imposters, as his credentials were not confirmed in the reply of the Navvāb Vazīr (of Avadh) and keeping in mind the instability of events at court. In the course of investigating his identity, it turned out that he was not only involved but lead the unseemly incident at the darvāzah of the dawlatkhānah-yi mubārak. Therefore, the purpose behind sending the khilʿat is apparent from the surreptitiously sealed shuqqah: to state Navvāb Munīr al-Dawlah Bahādur's complaints. Requests addressee to investigate whether this individual is culpable </p>
                        <p>Signed in English (next to lower right corner of text panel): <persName xml:lang="per-Latn-x-lc" key="ark:/81055/vdc_100166176930.0x000001 viaf_14929754" ref="http://lccn.loc.gov/nr93017163" role="aut">H[arry] Verelst</persName>
                        </p>
                        <p>Not dated </p>
                        <p>Narrow text panel of light zar afshānī or gold spray over a pale tinted ground; 2 upper cartouches (invocation and title) painted in gold; gold painted chatr above title cartouche; sar lawḥ above text panel in shape of low arch, filled with symmetrical scrolling floral ornament; painted gold floral motifs in diaper arrangement on plain paper ground; narrow outer border; angled corner (bottom right) </p>
                        <p>Bonhams, Knightsbridge, Sale 22524 (5 Nov 2014, 10:30), Lot 18 </p>
